questionTemplates.text:
M: Shall we make another pot of coffee?
W: Why not?
{a}

F: What's that man?
M: He's our new English teacher.
{a}

M: I don't think the shoes are fit for me. Can you show me a cheaper pair?
F: Of course. Just a moment.
{a}

W: What would you like to have, sir?
M: Well, I'd like to have an apple juice and a chicken sandwich.
{a}

M: Would you like a cup of tea?
W: I'd rather have a bottle of cola, please.
{a}

W: Hello, Mr. Smith. I'm afraid Dr. Brown won't be able to see you today. He's still waiting for a flight out of New York. He said he would meet you tomorrow afternoon. Is it OK?
M: Sounds good. Thank you for calling.
{a}

M: I know I promise to drive you to the airport next Thursday, but I'm afraid something has come up. They've called a special meeting at work.
W: No big deal. Karen said she was available as a back-up.
{a}

M: Would you mind turning down the TV a bit? I'm answering the phone.
W: Not at all.
{a}

W: Would you like a cup of tea?
M: No, thanks. But I like some coffee, please.
{a}

M: Now if you have any questions about the contract. I'll be happy to answer them.
W: Nothing comes to mind right now, but I'd like to go over all the articles of the contract once more before signing it.
{a}

M: Could you lend me your bike? Mine is broken.
F: I go to school by bike every day.
{a}

M: What happened to you? You're so late.
W: My bike had some trouble, and I had to walk.
{a}

M: I'm sorry, Madame. The train is somewhat behind the schedule. Take a seat and I'll tell you as soon as we know something definite.
W: Thank you. I'll just sit here and read the magazine in the meantime.
{a}

M: Next, shouldn't we get a telephone installed in the hall?
W: Fixing the shower pipe is far more important.
{a}

M: Did everyone have a good time on your visit to Paris?
W: Yes, but we all missed Bob.
{a}

F: What's the date today?
M: Four days later will be Teacher's Day.
{a}

W: Hi! I'm calling about the three-bedroom house you advertised in yesterday's paper. It sounds really nice.
M: It is - especially if you have children.
{a}

W: So, you're just back from a trip to India. What were you doing there?
M: The trip was intended to bring to the world's attention the fact that AIDS is not just an African disease; it's also endangering other countries, notably, India and Thailand.
{a}

W: Shall we go to the zoo on foot?
M: Why don't we go by bike? It's faster.
{a}

W: I have been waiting here for about half an hour. How did it take you so long to park the car?
M: I'm sorry, but I had to drive two blocks before I found a place to park.
{a}

W: Mary is fluent in English and she's just started to learn Japanese.
M: I hear she also knows a few words in Chinese and French.
{a}

W: Don't you have to go to work at 9:00?
M: No, I start at 9:30 today and 10:00 tomorrow.
{a}

M: I'd like to have that coat. But I haven't got enough money.
W: Shall I lend you some?
{a}

W: I forgot to tell you that Fred called last night to borrow your sleeping bag.
M: Oh, I saw him at the gym this morning, but he didn't say anything. So he must have asked somebody else.
{a}

M: Is it still raining?
W: Is it raining? Look at my clothes--they're wet.
{a}
